Census is clearly applied in this passage to the rents due from tenants for the term immediately following the taking of the honour into the king's hand. The corn (from the demesne manors apparently), ‘ Bladum maneriorum preter semen,' is accounted for separately at ΕΩ 10s. 7d. As this does not appear again, it must be included in the firma. Census is also the technical term for the fixed tribute paid by exempt monasteries to the Apostolic See. Again, census is applied to the rent of some lands held in 21 Henry ΙΙ by Alcher the huntsman and Richard his son (p. 79). The author's account is clearly inadequate; and in view of the fact that the census of many of the sorests‚ e. g. Nottingham, Cannock, the Dene, the New Forest and Feckenham, and the wood of Orcop, had remained unchanged from 31 Henry I to 21 Henry ΙΙ, it seems more reasonable to suppose that a census is an assessed or fixed rent as opposed to a firma which might or might not be altered. But even this distinction cannot be pressed, since in one instance (that of Westbury) the census in 21 Henry Π was half that received in 31 Henry I.
